      "text": "K अध्याँरो हो यो? It’s not the normal darkness of our bedroom in Bhaktapur. This is thick, like stage curtains falling all at once, trapping me inside the wings. I’m standing in the middle of the theater hall at Dostel. The spotlights are humming—that low, electric buzz that usually feels like home—but the air smells wrong. It doesn’t smell like wood dust and floor wax. It smells like diesel. Sunil’s auto rickshaw. And temple incense. The smell of a funeral.\n\nI try to move my legs, but they feel heavy, like I’m wading through mud. I look down and I’m wearing the red sari from my wedding, but it’s torn at the hem. My pendant—the one Dependra gave me—is burning against my chest. It’s hot, glowing red, searing into my skin. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am?\" \n\nThe voice comes from the back of the hall. It’s him. Prabin. He’s sitting in the front row, right where he always sits during PALM planning sessions. He looks normal. He’s wearing that grey hoodie he liked. He has his notebook open. But when he looks up, his eyes are just empty sockets, leaking thick, black theater paint.\n\n\"Sutnu vaisakyo ma\u0027am?\" he asks. His voice sounds like it’s coming from underwater. \n\nI try to scream, but my mouth is sewn shut with the same black thread we use for costume repairs. I can feel the stitches pulling against my lips, drawing blood. I taste copper. \n\nHe stands up and starts walking toward the stage. Each step sounds like a wet slap on the floor. Slap. Slap. Slap. He holds out his hand. His right hand. The index finger is gone. It’s just a jagged, raw stump, dripping onto the floorboards. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am, you told me to be kind,\" he whispers. He’s on the stage now, standing inches from me. \"You told me to leave. I followed your script, Shova Didi. Was this the ending you wrote for me?\"\n\nSuddenly, the stage isn\u0027t a stage anymore. It’s a field in Parsa. The heat is stifling. I can hear the sound of motorcycles in the distance—Saif and his friends. The shadows of 123 men start emerging from the tall grass. I see them all. Roshan is there, holding a toothbrush. Sanjay is there, holding a coil of rope. Pradeep, Sunil, the gym trainer who almost killed me—they’re all standing in a circle around us. They aren\u0027t looking at me. They’re looking at Prabin. \n\nThey all have missing fingers. \n\nThe guilt hits me like a physical blow. I fall to my knees. I can feel the wetness between my thighs—that sick, involuntary response my body has to terror. I hate it. I hate that even in this nightmare, my wiring is broken. My body is responding to the adrenaline of his murder as if it’s another one of my old addictions. I feel like a randi, a monster, a woman who can’t even mourn a dead boy without her skin betrayed her. \n\n\"I\u0027m sorry,\" I try to say through the stitches. \"I didn\u0027t know she would lie. I didn\u0027t know she would kill you.\"\n\nPrabin leans down. He presses the bloody stump of his finger against my forehead, right where my tika should be. It’s freezing cold. \n\n\"You knew what men do, Shova,\" he says. His voice is now a chorus of all the men I’ve ever slept with. \"You knew because you\u0027ve seen them at their worst. You chose the lie because you wanted to sleep next to Dependra tonight. You traded my life for your composure.\"\n\nThen, Samsa is there. She’s behind him, her face perfectly calm, her eyes dry. She’s holding a pair of theater scissors. She starts cutting the stitches on my mouth, but she’s taking the skin with it. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am, delete the trash,\" she whispers, giggling. \"Delete the trash, ma\u0027am.\"\n\nI wake up gasping, my hand clawing at my throat. \n\nThe room is silent. The moonlight is filtering through the curtains of our Bhaktapur house. I can hear Dependra’s steady, rhythmic breathing next to me. It’s the sound that usually anchors me to the earth, but tonight, it feels like an accusation. \n\nI’m shaking. My nightara is soaked in sweat. I reach down and touch my thighs—I’m wet. Really wet. A sob hitches in my throat, half-disgust, half-terror. I feel like I need to scrub my skin off with steel wool. I look at my husband’s back. He’s so peaceful. He has no idea that the woman sharing his bed is a vault of corpses. He thinks I’m stressed because of the \"Prabin situation\"—the lie I fed him. The lie he believed because he trusts me more than he trusts himself.\n\n*“Prabin ko ghar ma emergency parecha re, sir. Uu rati nai bhagyo. Phone pani switch off cha.”*\n\nI said those words to him yesterday morning with a straight face. I even managed a worried frown. I performed the \u0027concerned mentor\u0027 so perfectly that Dependra spent an hour trying to track down Prabin’s village contacts to see if he could help. I had to sit there and watch him be a good man while I carried the knowledge of a mutilated finger in my head.\n\nI slip out of bed, moving like a ghost. I go to the bathroom and lock the door. The \u0027click\u0027 of the lock triggers a flash of the dream—the theater door locking. I grip the sink until my knuckles are white. I look at myself in the mirror.\n\nWho is this woman?\n\nI see the teacher. I see the wife. I see the elegant, composed Shova Karki. But behind my eyes, I see the 123 men. I see the construction stairwells. And now, I see Prabin’s empty socket eyes. \n\nI turn on the cold water and splash my face, over and over. I need to feel something that isn\u0027t this suffocating guilt. I think about Prabin\u0027s parents. They’ll wait for a call that will never come. They’ll think their son abandoned them, or got into trouble, or just vanished. They’ll never have a body to bury. Because Samsa was \u0027angry.\u0027 Because I was \u0027scared.\u0027\n\nI lean my head against the cold tiles of the bathroom wall. I start doing my kegels—squeeze, release, squeeze, release. It’s a habit now, a way to reclaim my body, but tonight it feels like I’m just tightening the cage. I’m making myself \u0027tight\u0027 for a husband I’m betraying with every breath I take. \n\nWhat if I told him? What if I woke him up right now and said, *“Dependra, Prabin is dead. He was murdered because of a lie, and I’m helping the killer hide the evidence because I don\u0027t want you to know I’m a liar”*? \n\nHe would look at me with that devastating kindness. And then he would call the police. And then the men in Parsa would come. Dostel would be closed. The reputation he spent a decade building would be ashes. Samsa would be killed. Maybe I would be too.\n\nI can’t. I’m a coward. I’ve always been a coward. I ran from my addiction into his arms, and now I’m running from a murder into this silence. \n\nI walk back into the bedroom. The floorboards creak. Dependra stirs, turning over. He reaches out an arm, searching for me in his sleep. I slide back into bed, fitting my body against his. He smells like sandalwood and home. He pulls me closer, his hand resting on my hip, his thumb brushing the skin just above my pajama waistband. \n\n\"Shova...?\" he mumbles, his voice thick with sleep. \"Sanchai chau? K bhayo?\"\n\n\"Kahi bhako chaina,\" I whisper into his chest. My voice is steady. The theater training never fails. \"Nindra lagena... tyo Prabin ko chinta lagira thiyo.\"\n\n\"Uu thikai huncha, nani. Don\u0027t worry. Bholi pheri try garchu usko family lai contact garna,\" he says, kissing the top of my head. \n\nI close my eyes. I can feel my heart thumping against his ribs. I wonder if he can feel the rot inside me. I wonder if he can smell the diesel and the blood on my breath. \n\nI lie there in the dark, waiting for sleep to take me back to the stage, back to the field, back to the boy with the missing finger. This is my life now. This is the performance I have to give every day until I die. \n\nI’m Shova Karki. I’m 29. I’m a theater teacher. And I am the grave where Prabin is buried. \n\n\"I love you,\" I whisper to Dependra. \n\nAnd for the first time in a year, I’m not sure if I mean it, or if it’s just the next line in the script.",
