      "text": "It started on Tuesday afternoon, right as the sun was hitting the windows of the theater hall at Dostel. \n\nI was standing at the front, explaining the concept of *Subtext* to the PALM members. I was talking about how what a character says is rarely what they mean. I was being \"Shova Ma\u0027am\"—composed, hands moving gracefully, voice modulated. \n\nAnd then I saw him.\n\nHe was standing by the equipment locker in the back. Same grey hoodie. His hands were tucked into his pockets. He was just... watching. My heart didn\u0027t just race; it stopped. It literally felt like a stone in my chest. I stumbled over a word—*“Subtext bhandale... uuu...”*—and I had to grip the edge of the podium so hard my knuckles turned white.\n\nI blinked. I expected him to be gone. That’s how it works in the movies, right? You blink and the ghost vanishes. But he didn\u0027t. He just tilted his head, exactly the way Prabin used to do when he was thinking about a lighting cue.\n\n\"Ma\u0027am? Sab thik cha?\" Samsa asked from the front row. \n\nI looked at her. She was looking right at the spot where he was standing. Her eyes went right through him. She didn\u0027t see the blood dripping from his hoodie onto the floorboards. She didn\u0027t see the way his neck was twisted at an impossible angle. \n\n\"Ah... thik cha. Dherai light bhayera aankha tirimiri bhayo,\" I lied. I forced a smile. I finished the session. I don\u0027t remember a single word I said. All I remember is the sound of his phantom footsteps following me out of the room.\n\nNow, it’s been three days, and he hasn\u0027t left.\n\nHe’s there when I’m teaching at school in Bhaktapur. He sits in the back of my classroom, staring at the blackboard. He’s there when I’m walking to the bus stop. I see him in the reflection of the shop windows, walking three paces behind me. He doesn\u0027t speak. He just *is.* \n\nThe worst part is the smell. Everywhere I go, the air turns heavy with the scent of wet earth and diesel. It’s so strong I sometimes have to cover my nose with a handkerchief, pretending I’m sensitive to the Kathmandu pollution. But nobody else smells it. Dependra kissed me this morning and told me I smelled like jasmine. I wanted to scream. *How can you smell jasmine when there’s a dead boy in the corner of our bedroom smelling like a ditch?*\n\nYes. He’s in our house now.\n\nLast night, I was making tea for Dependra. I turned around to grab the sugar, and Prabin was standing by the fridge. He was holding his hand out—the one with the missing finger. He pointed it at the tea. \n\n\"Sutnu vaisakyo ma\u0027am?\" he whispered. \n\nI dropped the sugar jar. It shattered on the tile floor, white crystals spraying everywhere. \n\n\"Shova! K bhayo?\" Dependra came running from the living room. He stepped right through Prabin. He literally walked through the space where the boy was standing, and for a second, Prabin’s image flickered like a bad video signal. \n\n\"Kehi haina... haat bata चिप्लियो,\" I said, my voice shaking. I knelt down to pick up the glass, my hands trembling so much I cut my thumb. I didn\u0027t even feel it. I just watched Prabin. He was looking at Dependra with those empty, paint-filled eyes. \n\n\"Timi dherai stretch bhairachau, Shova,\" Dependra said, kneeling next to me to help. He took my hand and saw the blood. He sucked in a breath and immediately put my thumb in his mouth to stop the bleeding. \n\nIt was supposed to be sweet. It was supposed to be the man I love taking care of me. But all I could see was Prabin standing over us, his missing finger pointing at Dependra’s head. \n\nI feel like I’m going insane. Is this what happens? Is this the \u0027relapse\u0027? I thought the addiction was the worst thing that could happen to my brain, but this is different. This is the guilt taking a physical form because I have no one to tell. I’m carrying 123 men and one dead boy, and the weight is finally cracking my skull open.\n\nI can\u0027t look at Samsa anymore. Every time I see her at Dostel, I see him standing right behind her, his hand resting on her shoulder. She goes about her day, laughing with the other girls, studying, acting... she’s moving on. She’s erased him from her phone and her life. But he’s stuck to me. Because I’m the one who validated the lie. I’m the one who gave the \u0027official\u0027 story. \n\nI went to the bathroom at Dostel today just to be alone. I locked the door and slumped against the wall. I reached into my kurta and started touching myself—not because I was horny, but because I needed to feel something *real.* I needed the friction, the heat, the physical proof that I was alive and he wasn\u0027t. \n\nBut as I closed my eyes, I felt a cold draft. I opened them, and Prabin was sitting on the edge of the sink. He wasn\u0027t looking at my body. He was looking at my face. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am, k gareko?\" he asked. \n\nI stopped. I pulled my hand away as if the skin was on fire. I felt sick. I felt like a randi all over again, exposed",
