      "text": "I scrambled to fix my clothes, my fingers fumbling with the fabric of my kurta as if I’d been caught by a living person. My heart was thumping so hard I could see it vibrating against my ribs. \n\n\"Niskiyau... please niskiyau,\" I whispered, my voice breaking. I didn\u0027t look at him. I stared at the bathroom tiles, counting the cracks. *One, two, three.* \n\nBut the air stayed cold. The smell of wet earth didn\u0027t go away. \n\nI washed my hands with so much soap it started to sting, scrubbing until the skin turned pink. I needed to wash the feeling of his eyes off me. I looked in the mirror, avoided the space behind my reflection, and walked out. \n\nThe hallway of Dostel was full of life. Students were heading to the dining hall. I could hear the clinking of plates and the smell of tarkari. It was so normal it made me want to scream. I saw Samsa walking toward me, her face glowing. She’d put on a bit of lipstick today. She looked like a girl who had finally put a tragedy behind her. \n\nAnd right next to her, walking in perfect step, was Prabin. \n\nHe was leaning toward her ear, his mouth moving as if he was whispering a secret. Samsa laughed at something another girl said, stepping right through Prabin’s translucent chest. I had to lean against the wall to keep from falling. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am? Sanchai hunuhuncha?\" Samsa stopped, looking concerned. \"Tapai kasto seto dekhinu bhako cha.\"\n\n\"Thik chu, Samsa. Jau... khana khana jau,\" I said, my voice sounding like it belonged to someone else. I didn\u0027t look at her. I looked at the floor where Prabin’s feet should have been. There were no shadows. Just the polished wood. \n\nI left Dostel without saying goodbye to anyone. I couldn\u0027t find Dependra. I didn\u0027t want to find him. I just needed to be outside. \n\nI walked through the streets of Lalitpur, my feet moving on autopilot. Kathmandu was its usual mess—the honking, the dust, the people shoving past. But in every crowd, I saw him. I saw him sitting on the back of a passing motorbike. I saw him standing in the queue at a chiya pasal. Every time I turned a corner, he was there, waiting. \n\nBy the time I reached home in Bhaktapur, I was shivering despite the evening heat. \n\nThe house was quiet. Dependra wasn\u0027t home yet. I went straight to the kitchen, needing to do something—anything—to keep my hands busy. I started chopping onions. *Slice, slice, slice.* The sharp smell stung my eyes, giving me an excuse to cry. \n\n\"Shova?\" \n\nI jumped, the knife slipping and nicking my finger. I turned around. It was Dependra. He’d come in through the back door. \n\n\"Laa, k gareko timile? Herana, ragat aayo,\" he said, dropping his bag and rushing to me. He took my hand, his touch warm and real. \"Timi dherai नै distracted chau bholi-parsi. K bhako ho? Prabin ko barema kehi news aayo ra?\"\n\nI looked past his shoulder. Prabin was standing in our kitchen doorway. He was holding up his own hand, showing me the stump where his finger used to be. \n\n\"Nai, kehi news chaina,\" I said, my throat dry. I looked back at Dependra. I wanted to tell him. I wanted to collapse into him and tell him that his favorite student was dead and I was seeing his ghost in our kitchen. I wanted to tell him about the 123 men. I wanted to tell him everything so the weight would stop crushing my bones. \n\n\"Timi sutna jau, ma khana banauchhu,\" Dependra said, kissing my forehead. \"You’re exhausted, Shova. Take a rest, hai?\"\n\nI nodded and walked toward the bedroom. I felt like I was walking to my own execution. \n\nI lay down in the dark, staring at the ceiling. The house was full of the sounds of Dependra moving in the kitchen—the clatter of pans, the whistle of the pressure cooker. It was the sound of a happy marriage. A normal life. \n\nThen I felt the bed dip. \n\nI didn\u0027t turn around. I couldn\u0027t. I stayed frozen, my breath hitched in my chest. A cold, damp hand touched my shoulder. I could smell the diesel, the temple incense, the rot. \n\n\"Ma\u0027am,\" Prabin’s voice whispered in my ear. It wasn\u0027t just his voice anymore. It was Roshan’s voice. It was Sanjay’s. It was the sound of 123 men breathing in a dark room. \"Ma\u0027am, kasto loose jhut boleko? Dependra sir lai thaha bhayo bhane k huncha?\"\n\nI squeezed my eyes shut, tears leaking out and soaking into the pillow. \n\n\"Go away... please go away,\" I sobbed into the fabric. \n\n\"I can\u0027t go away, Shova Didi,\" he whispered. \"You buried me in your silence. I\u0027m part of the house now. I\u0027m part of you.\"\n\nI felt a sudden, sharp pressure on my throat. Not enough to kill me, but enough to remind me of Kiran’s hands in that gym. The fear made my body spike—that sickening, familiar warmth spreading between my legs. I hated myself. I was lying in my husband’s bed, being haunted by a boy I helped murder, and my broken, addicted body was responding as if it were a kink. \n\nI reached down, my hand shaking, and gripped the fabric of my leggings. I needed to stop. I needed to be a good wife. I needed to be Shova Karki. \n\nBut as the pressure on my throat tightened, I saw the 123 men standing in the shadows of my bedroom. They were all watching. They were all waiting. \n\n\"Shova? Khana bhayo!\" Dependra called from the other room. \n\nThe pressure on my neck vanished. The coldness lifted. \n\nI sat up, gasping for air, my hand flying to my throat. I looked around. The room was empty. No ghost. No men. Just the moonlight and the smell of Dependra’s tarkari. \n\nI got out of bed, my legs shaking. I walked to the mirror and turned on the light. There were no marks on my neck. My skin was smooth. My pendant was straight. \n\nI looked at my reflection. I looked perfect. \n\n\"Aaudai chu!\" I called back, my voice clear and steady. \n\nI walked out of the room, putting on the mask. I smiled at my husband. I sat at the table. I ate the food. I laughed at his jokes. I performed the part of the happy wife. \n\nBut as I looked at him across the table, I saw Prabin sitting right behind him, his grey hoodie stained with blood, his empty eyes never leaving mine. \n\nI’m not seeing a ghost. I’m seeing my own soul. And it’s not going anywhere.",
