      "text": "(I’m sitting at the dining table. Dependra is right across from me, talking about a new project for the LIME club. He’s eating with his hands, his movements calm and rhythmic. The smell of his favorite dal is in the air. It should be safe here.)\n\n(Then Prabin’s voice cuts through the room. It’s not a whisper this time. It’s clear. It’s loud. It sounds exactly like he did during our last PALM meeting.)\n\n\"Ma\u0027am, can you see me???\"\n\n(My spoon clatters against the plate. I freeze, my eyes locked on the empty chair next to Dependra. Prabin is sitting there. He’s leaning forward, his elbows on the table, right next to Dependra’s plate. His face is pale, the grey hoodie damp with what looks like river water. The smell of diesel and rot suddenly overwhelms the scent of the food.)\n\n\"Shova? K bhayo?\" Dependra looks at me, his hand stopping mid-air. \"Timi k heri racheu tesari?\"\n\n(I can\u0027t look away. Prabin is staring at me, his head tilted. He looks so... solid. So real. I can see the individual threads of his hoodie. I can see the black paint leaking from his eyes, staining his cheeks.)\n\n\"Can you see me, Ma\u0027am?\" Prabin asks again. He reaches out his hand—the one with the missing finger—and brushes it against Dependra’s cheek. \n\n(I let out a small, choked gasp. My body reacts instantly—that sick, electric jolt of fear that turns into a heavy, unwanted heat between my legs. I hate it. I hate that my body is betraying me while my husband is sitting right there. I grip the edge of the table until my nails dig into the wood.)\n\n\"Nai...\" I whisper, my voice trembling.\n\n\"Nai k?\" Dependra asks, his brow furrowed. He reaches out to touch my hand. \"Shova, timro face kasto nilo dekhiracha. Sanchai chau ni? Tarkari man parena ra?\"\n\n\"Man parecha... I\u0027m just... dherai thakeko chu, Dependra,\" I lie, my eyes darting back to Prabin. \n\n(Prabin is standing up now. He walks behind Dependra, putting his arms around my husband’s neck. He looks like a lover. He looks like one of the 123 men. He looks like my own damnation.)\n\n\"Tell him, Ma\u0027am,\" Prabin whispers into Dependra’s ear. Dependra doesn\u0027t move. He doesn\u0027t feel the cold. He doesn\u0027t smell the death. \"Tell him I\u0027m here. Tell him why I\u0027m here. Can you see the finger, Ma\u0027am? It\u0027s in the kitchen. It\u0027s in your tea.\"\n\n(I feel a wave of nausea so strong I have to push back from the table. I stand up, my chair screeching against the floor. I can\u0027t breathe. The air in the room feels like it\u0027s been replaced with swamp water.)\n\n\"Ma washroom gayera aauchhu,\" I say, not waiting for an answer. \n\n(I bolt from the room, my heart hammering. I lock the bathroom door and lean against it, sliding down until I’m sitting on the cold floor. I pull my knees to my chest and bury my face in my hands. I’m shaking. I’m wet. I’m terrified.)\n\n\"I can see you,\" I whisper into the darkness of my palms. \"I see you, Prabin. Please... please just stop. Maile delete gare... I deleted everything. Just go away.\"\n\n\"You can\u0027t delete a ghost, Shova Didi,\" his voice comes from the bathtub. \n\n(I look up. He’s sitting on the edge of the tub, his legs dangling. He’s holding the blue toothbrush—Roshan’s toothbrush—that I kept in my drawer for years. He’s playing with the bristles.)\n\n\"123 men. And now me,\" Prabin says, his voice devoid of emotion. \"I\u0027m the 124th, aren\u0027t I? The one you can\u0027t fuck your way out of. The one you can\u0027t hide with a \u0027huss\u0027 and a smile.\"\n\n(I crawl toward the toilet and vomit. It’s mostly just yellow bile and the tea I had earlier. I stay there, panting, my forehead resting on the cold porcelain.)\n\n\"Shova? Are you okay in there?\" Dependra is knocking on the door. His voice is full of that pure, honest concern that makes me want to die. \"Open the door, nani. Timi birami chau jasto cha.\"\n\n(I look at Prabin. He’s standing right behind me now, his hand hovering over my head as if he’s going to bless me or choke me. I don’t know which is worse.)\n\n\"Can you see me, Ma\u0027am?\" he asks one more time, his voice a low, vibrating hum that fills the small room.\n\n(I close my eyes and take a deep, shaky breath. I reach for a towel and wipe my mouth. I fix my hair. I touch my pendant. I perform.)\n\n\"I\u0027m fine, Dependra! Just a bit of food poisoning, jasto cha. Ekchin ma niskinchu,\" I call out. My voice is steady. Perfect.\n\n(I open my eyes. Prabin is gone. The smell of diesel is gone. The room is just a bathroom again.)\n\n(But when I look in the mirror to fix my tika, I see a small, bloody smudge on my forehead. Exactly where a finger would have touched it.)\n\n(I don\u0027t wash it off immediately. I just stare at it. I can see him. I will always see him.)",
