      "text": "(I’m frozen on the bathroom floor, the cold tiles pressing against my thighs. My breath is coming in short, jagged hitches. The sound of his voice—so vulnerable, so *Prabin*—is a thousand times worse than the silent, staring ghost from before. He sounds like a child. He sounds like the student who used to ask me for advice on lighting plots.)\n\n\"Prabin...\" (I whisper his name so quietly it’s barely a breath. I look at the bathtub where he’s sitting. He looks so small. So lonely. The paint leaking from his eyes looks like real tears now.)\n\n\"Shova? K bhanyo timile? Prabin?\" (Dependra’s voice comes through the door, sharp with confusion. I freeze. My heart is a frantic bird hitting the cage of my ribs.)\n\n\"Nai... kehi haina! Maile... maile tyo script ko dialogue samjhirako,\" I shout back, my voice cracking. I have to bite my lip to keep from sobbing. (I can feel the fear-wetness between my legs, a hot, shameful contrast to the freezing draft Prabin is bringing into the room. I hate my body. I hate that I’m like this.)\n\n(I turn back to the bathtub, crawling on my hands and knees until I’m right in front of him. I reach out a hand, trembling, but I stop before I touch him. I’m afraid my hand will just pass through his grey hoodie like smoke.)\n\n\"I can see you,\" I whisper, the tears finally spilling over. \"Prabin, I see you. I\u0027m so sorry. I\u0027m so, so sorry. Maile timlai jhut bolna laye... I told you to leave. Maile timlai protect garna sakina.\"\n\n(The smell of diesel is so thick now I can almost taste it. It’s the smell of his end. The smell of the road to Parsa.)\n\n\"Lonely...?\" (The word breaks my heart. I know loneliness. I spent years surrounded by 123 men and I was never more alone than when they were inside me. But this? To be dead and invisible? To watch the world move on while you\u0027re stuck in the corner of a room?)\n\n\"Ma k garu, Prabin? Bhana na malai. I can\u0027t tell anyone. If I tell them, everything burns. Dostel sakincha. Dependra sir sakincha. Samsa...\" (I choke on her name. Disgust rises in my throat again, bitter as bile.) \"She lied. She told him you were forcing her. She\u0027s the one who sent him, Prabin. Did you know that? Did you know she did that to you?\"\n\n(I look at the door. Dependra is still there. I can hear him shifting his weight, waiting. My perfect, kind husband is inches away from a horror he can\u0027t even imagine.)\n\n\"Timi yaha kina ayeko? Why me? Is it because I\u0027m the only one who knows the truth? Is it because I\u0027m as broken as you are now?\"\n\n(I lean my head against the side of the tub, close to where his phantom knees are. I\u0027m crying openly now, no longer trying to hide the sound.)\n\n\"Please... don\u0027t be lonely. I\u0027m here. Ma herirachu timlai. I won\u0027t ignore you. But you have to be quiet, Prabin. If Dependra sir finds out... he\u0027ll try to find your body. He\u0027ll go to the police. And Saif... Saif will kill him too. Do you want that? Do you want more blood?\"\n\n(I look up at him, my face a mess of tears and smeared tika. I reach out and touch the pendant at my throat, the metal cold and unforgiving.)\n\n\"Ma timlai bhulchau bhanna sakdina. I will see you every day. This is my punishment, isn\u0027t it? 123 men I wanted to forget... and one boy I’ll never be allowed to.\"\n\n\"Ma\u0027am...?\" (Dependra knocks again, louder this time.) \"Shova, open the door. Aile nai. You\u0027re talking to yourself. I’m getting worried.\"\n\n(I look at Prabin. He’s staring at me, his empty sockets filled with a desperate, silent longing. I have to go back. I have to put the mask back on. I have to be the woman who didn\u0027t just watch her student be erased.)\n\n\"I have to go,\" I whisper to him. \"Stay here. Please. Just stay here in the dark. I\u0027ll come back. I promise. I won\u0027t leave you alone.\"\n\n(I stand up, wiping my face with a wet towel, scrubbing until it hurts. I fix my kurta. I take a deep breath, forcing my lungs to expand. I turn the lock.)\n\n(I open the door and walk into Dependra’s arms, burying my face in his chest so he can’t see my eyes. He holds me tight, and for a second, I feel safe. But over his shoulder, through the open bathroom door, I see Prabin standing by the mirror, watching us. He’s holding up his hand. The four fingers and the stump.)\n\n\"I see you,\" I think, my heart breaking. \"I see you.\"",
