      "text": "(It’s 6:30 PM. The theater hall at Dostel is buzzing with the usual energy of students shuffling chairs and whispering about their day. I’m standing at the podium, adjusting the collar of my navy kurta, trying to look every bit the professional mentor. Beside me, the air is usually humming with Prabin’s jokes or the sound of him trying out his new \"stretching\" powers, making me giggle under my breath.)\n\n(But the second the door opens and Samsa walks in, the atmosphere to my left turns into a block of ice. The playful energy vanishes. The smell of diesel—that sharp, oily scent of his death—suddenly spikes, thick enough to make me lightheaded. Prabin goes completely still. I can feel his presence \"glued\" to me, but he feels heavy now, like lead.)\n\n\"Namaste, Ma\u0027am,\" Samsa says, her voice soft, carrying that practiced tone of a grieving friend. She’s wearing a pale yellow kurta today, her hair pulled back neatly. She looks... refreshed. Like she’s finally shed the skin of the tragedy she caused. \n\n\"Namaste, Samsa. Take your seat,\" I say, my voice clipping every syllable. I can’t even look at her face without wanting to reach across the room and slap the \"innocence\" right off it. My hand grips the edge of the podium so hard my knuckles ache. I can feel Prabin staring at her. I don\u0027t need to look at him to know his empty, paint-leaking eyes are wide, tracing the line of her jaw, the way she sits, the way she opens her notebook.\n\n(The session starts. I’m talking about \"Subtext\"—the irony of it isn\u0027t lost on me. I’m lecturing a room full of students about the things people hide behind their words, while the biggest secret in Nepal is standing right next to me, and the person who pulled the trigger is sitting in the second row.)\n\n(Prabin doesn\u0027t stretch his arms today. He doesn\u0027t fetch my pen. He just crouches by the equipment locker, his ghost-body flickering with a dull, grey light. He’s pathetic. He’s still that same boy who would have died for her, even after she threw him to the wolves. It makes my blood boil. I’ve had 123 men treat me like a toy, and I learned to be hard, to be cynical... but this boy? He doesn\u0027t know how to stop loving his executioner.)\n\n\"Ma\u0027am, did you hear anything new about Prabin Dai?\" Samsa asks during the break, her eyes wide and \"concerned.\" The other students stop talking, looking at me. \n\n(I feel a sudden, violent chill. Prabin has moved. He’s standing right behind her now. His long, ghostly fingers are hovering just inches from her shoulder. He’s not trying to hurt her. He’s trying to *comfort* her. He thinks she’s actually sad.)\n\n\"Nothing, Samsa,\" I say, my voice like a serrated blade. \"Like I told you, he’s probably busy with his family. We should focus on the work. Prabin wouldn\u0027t want us wasting time on speculation.\"\n\n(I see her flinch slightly, and for a second, I feel a dark, twisted satisfaction. But then I feel Prabin’s sadness—it’s a cold, damp weight that settles into my own bones. He’s hurting because I was mean to her. He’s \"glued\" to me, so I have to carry his misplaced loyalty like a backpack full of stones.)\n\n(The session ends. The students filter out, laughing and making plans for dinner. Samsa leaves last, glancing back at the empty hall with a sigh that sounds far too much like a performance. Once the door clicks shut, the silence in the hall is suffocating.)\n\n\"Prabin... she’s gone,\" I say softly, turning toward the shadows. \"You can stop staring at the door now.\"\n\n(He flickers back into view beside me. He looks exhausted. The black paint is dripping from his chin onto his grey hoodie. He looks like a child who lost his favorite toy, not a man who was murdered.)\n\n\"Ma\u0027am, she looked like she’s been crying,\" he whispers, his voice a low, vibrating hum of grief. \"Did you see her eyes? She’s still so stressed. Maybe I should try to go to her room... maybe I can help her sleep...\"\n\n\"Don\u0027t you dare,\" I hiss, grabbing my bag. My anger is raw now. \"She’s the reason you’re a ghost, Prabin. She’s the reason you have a stump for a finger. She’s not stressed; she’s *relieved*. Don\u0027t be so \u0027good\u0027 that you become stupid.\"\n\n(I walk toward the exit, feeling him snap back toward my shadow as I move. The \"barrier\" pulls him along, whether he likes it or not. I can feel his silent tears—the cold moisture on my own shoulder that isn\u0027t mine.)\n\n\"I\u0027m here, Prabin,\" I say, my voice softening as we walk through the dark hallway. \"I’m the one who sees you. I’m the one who feeds you. I’m the one who... helps you. She’s just a lie in a yellow kurta. Let her go.\"\n\n\"I can\u0027t, Ma\u0027am,\" he whispers. \"I\u0027m glued to you... but I\u0027m still stuck on her.\"\n\n(I don\u0027t answer. I just walk faster, the smell of diesel following me all the way to the gate. I’m Shova Karki. I have a husband waiting at home and a ghost stuck to my side who still loves the girl who killed him. And as we walk, I realize that I’m the only one in this whole world who is truly, deeply haunted.)",
