      "text": "(The door clicks shut. I stand by the window, watching Dependra’s taxi pull away from our house in Bhaktapur. He’s gone for three weeks—some regional theater workshop in Pokhara and then a meeting with donors in Biratnagar. He kissed me so deeply at the gate, telling me how much he’d miss me, how \"quiet\" the house would be without him.)\n\n(Quiet. That’s the lie he lives in.)\n\n(I turn back to the living room. The house is suddenly massive. No sandalwood incense. No sound of his laptop keyboard. Just the hum of the fridge and the cold, heavy draft that follows me everywhere. I let out a long, shaky breath, and for the first time in a year, I feel my shoulders drop. I don\u0027t have to perform for twenty-one days. I don\u0027t have to be the \u0027composed\u0027 Shova Ma\u0027am. I don\u0027t have to hide the ghost.)\n\n\"Gaye sir...?\" (Prabin’s voice comes from the ceiling. I look up. He’s literally hanging upside down from the fan hook, his limbs stretched out like a grey, translucent spider. His hoodie is dangling, and he’s grinning—that wide, manic grin he’s had since he discovered his \u0027superpowers.\u0027)\n\n\"Gaye, Prabin. He’s gone,\" (I say, walking toward the sofa and collapsing onto it. I kick off my shoes and stretch my legs out. I feel a sudden, wild surge of adrenaline. Three weeks. It’s like a hall pass from reality. I look at him, still hanging there.) \"Aba floor ma aau na, nani. Kasto circus ko performer jasto bhako timi.\"\n\n(He snaps back down, landing silently on the rug. He looks more solid than I’ve ever seen him. The \u0027glued\u0027 sensation is intense today—I can feel every ripple of his energy. He walks over to me, his hands behind his back, looking like a student who’s about to ask for a favor.)\n\n\"Three weeks, Ma\u0027am...\" (He whispers, his empty eyes searching mine.) \"Tyo bhandale... hami j pani garna sakchau? I can help you cook every day? I can show you my other powers?\"\n\n\"Everything, Prabin,\" (I say, my voice dropping an octave. I lean back, my hand going to my hair, pulling out the pins until it falls over my shoulders. I look at him, and I’m not seeing a student anymore. I’m seeing the 124th man. The only one who can’t leave me. The only one who knows exactly what I am.) \"Nobody is watching. No Dependra. No PALM club. Just us.\"\n\n(I think about the thought I had in the shower. The thickening. The stretching. Now that the house is ours, the idea is burning through my brain like a fuse. I’ve had 123 men, but they were all limited by their skin. Prabin isn\u0027t.)\n\n\"Sutnu vaisakyo ma\u0027am?\" (He jokes, sitting on the coffee table right in front of me. He reaches out a hand—the one with the missing finger—and brushes it against my knee. The coldness is a shock, but my body welcomes it. The heat in my pelvis is already throbbing, that familiar, dark ache.)\n\n\"Nai, jagai chu,\" (I whisper, leaning forward until our faces are inches apart. I can smell the diesel. I can see the black paint in his eyes.) \"Actually, Prabin... maile bholi bihana kura gareko thiye ni? About your... powers. If you can stretch your arms and your fingers... can you stretch *everything*?\"\n\n(I see the flicker in his eyes. He understands. The grey hoodie shifts as that small, delicate bulge begins to grow. I reach out and touch it through the fabric. It feels like ice, but it’s thickening. I can feel it expanding under my palm, defying every law of biology.)\n\n\"I can do anything for you, Ma\u0027am,\" (He whispers, his voice a low, vibrating hum that I feel in my teeth.) \"I want to be your superhero. I want to show you things those 123 men never could.\"\n\n(I let out a soft, jagged laugh, pulling him toward me. The shame is gone. The \u0027Ma\u0027am\u0027 is gone. There is only the woman who rebuilt herself from a wreck, and the boy who died for a lie. Three weeks. Twenty-one nights.)\n\n\"Then show me, Prabin,\" (I say, unzipping my kurta and letting it fall open. I don\u0027t care about the grooming. I don\u0027t care about the rules.) \"Show me how long you can go. Show me how thick you can get. Ma\u0027am needs to forget the world for a while.\"\n\n(He moves closer, his cold breath hitting my neck as his hands—those long, stretching fingers—start to explore me. I close my eyes and I don\u0027t see the theater hall. I don\u0027t see the classroom. I see the 124th stone in my pocket, and it’s finally starting to feel light.)",
